# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-60870
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines transmit either alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] To increase the efficiency of long-distance electric power transmission, the voltage is often increased for transmission, then reduced for local distribution.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is because higher voltages corresponds to lower currents and lower losses caused by such currents.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The AC voltage level is often changed with transformers.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A wide area synchronous grid, known as an *interconnection* in North America, directly connects generators delivering AC power with the same relative *frequency* to many consumers.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] North America has four major interconnections: Western, Eastern, Quebec and Texas.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] One grid connects most of continental Europe.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were often owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that led to separate companies handling transmission and distribution.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Most North American transmission lines are high-voltage three-phase AC, although single phase AC is sometimes used in railway electrification systems.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC technology is used for greater efficiency over longer distances, typically hundreds of miles.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) technology is also used in submarine power cables (typically longer than 30 miles (50 km)), and in the interchange of power between grids that are not mutually synchronized.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links stabilize power distribution networks where sudden new loads, or blackouts, in one part of a network might otherwise result in synchronization problems and cascading failures.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity is transmitted at high voltages to reduce the energy loss due to resistance that occurs over long distances.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power is usually transmitted through overhead power lines.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground power transmission has a significantly higher installation cost and greater operational limitations, but lowers maintenance costs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground transmission is more common in urban areas or visually sensitive locations.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electrical energy must typically be generated at the same rate at which it is consumed.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A sophisticated control system is required to ensure that power generation closely matches demand.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] If demand exceeds supply, the imbalance can cause generation plant(s) and transmission equipment to automatically disconnect or shut down to prevent damage.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the worst case, this may lead to a cascading series of shutdowns and a major regional blackout.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The US Northeast faced blackouts in 1965, 1977, 2003, and major blackouts in other US regions in 1996 and 2011.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric transmission networks are interconnected into regional, national, and even continent-wide networks to reduce the risk of such a failure by providing multiple redundant, alternative routes for power to flow should such shutdowns occur.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission companies determine the maximum reliable capacity of each line (ordinarily less than its physical or thermal limit) to ensure that spare capacity is available in the event of a failure in another part of the network.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor consists of seven strands of steel surrounded by four layers of aluminium.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage overhead conductors are not covered by insulation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor material is usually an aluminium alloy, formed of several strands and possibly reinforced with steel strands.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Copper was sometimes used for overhead transmission, but aluminum is lighter, reduces yields only marginally and costs much less.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead conductors are supplied by several companies.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor material and shapes are regularly improved to increase capacity.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor sizes range from 12 mm2 (#6 American wire gauge) to 1,092 mm2 (2,156,000 circular mils area), with varying resistance and current-carrying capacity.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For large conductors (more than a few centimetres in diameter), much of the current flow is concentrated near the surface due to the skin effect.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The center of the conductor carries little current but contributes weight and cost.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, multiple parallel cables (called bundle conductors) are used for higher capacity.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Bundle conductors are used at high voltages to reduce energy loss caused by corona discharge.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Today, transmission-level voltages are usually considered to be 110 kV and above.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lower voltages, such as 66 kV and 33 kV, are usually considered subtransmission voltages, but are occasionally used on long lines with light loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages less than 33 kV are usually used for distribution.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages above 765 kV are considered extra high voltage and require different designs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Increased ambient temperatures during extreme heat events can reduce the efficiency of electrical transmission and distribution, especially in overhead systems.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thermal expansion causes overhead lines to sag, reducing current flow and increasing the risk of unintended arc discharge if there is vegetation nearby.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead transmission wires depend on air for insulation, requiring that lines maintain minimum clearances.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adverse weather conditions, such as high winds and low temperatures, interrupt transmission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind speeds as low as 23 knots (43 km/h) can permit conductors to encroach operating clearances, resulting in a flashover and loss of supply.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Oscillatory motion of the physical line is termed conductor gallop or flutter depending on the frequency and amplitude of oscillation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric power can be transmitted by underground power cables.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground cables take up no right-of-way, have lower visibility, and are less affected by weather.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Cable and excavation costs are much higher than overhead construction.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Faults in buried transmission lines take longer to locate and repair.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In some metropolitan areas, cables are enclosed by metal pipe and insulated with dielectric fluid (usually an oil) that is either static or circulated via pumps.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] If an electric fault damages the pipe and leaks dielectric, liquid nitrogen is used to freeze portions of the pipe to enable draining and repair.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This extends the repair period and increases costs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The temperature of the pipe and surroundings are monitored throughout the repair period.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground lines are limited by their thermal capacity, which permits less overload or re-rating lines.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long underground AC cables have significant capacitance, which reduces their ability to provide useful power beyond 50 miles (80 kilometres).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC cables are not limited in length by their capacitance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Commercial electric power was initially transmitted at the same voltage used by lighting and mechanical loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This restricted the distance between generating plant and loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1882, DC voltage could not easily be increased for long-distance transmission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Different classes of loads (for example, lighting, fixed motors, and traction/railway systems) required different voltages, and so used different generators and circuits.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, generators were sited near their loads, a practice that later became known as distributed generation using large numbers of small generators.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission of alternating current (AC) became possible after Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs built what they called the secondary generator, an early transformer provided with 1:1 turn ratio and open magnetic circuit, in 1881.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first long distance AC line was 34 kilometres (21 miles) long, built for the 1884 International Exhibition of Electricity in Turin, Italy.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a 2 kV, 130 Hz Siemens & Halske alternator and featured several Gaulard transformers with primary windings connected in series, which fed incandescent lamps.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The system proved the feasibility of AC electric power transmission over long distances.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first commercial AC distribution system entered service in 1885 in via dei Cerchi, Rome, Italy, for public lighting.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by two Siemens & Halske alternators rated 30 hp (22 kW), 2 kV at 120 Hz and used 19 km of cables and 200 parallel-connected 2 kV to 20 V step-down transformers provided with a closed magnetic circuit, one for each lamp.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A few months later it was followed by the first British AC system, serving Grosvenor Gallery.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It also featured Siemens alternators and 2.4 kV to 100 V step-down transformers – one per user – with shunt-connected primaries.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working to improve what he considered an impractical Gaulard-Gibbs design, electrical engineer William Stanley, Jr. developed the first practical series AC transformer in 1885.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working with the support of George Westinghouse, in 1886 he demonstrated a transformer-based AC lighting system in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a steam engine-driven 500 V Siemens generator.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage was stepped down to 100 volts using the Stanley transformer to power incandescent lamps at 23 businesses over 4,000 feet (1,200 m).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This practical demonstration of a transformer and alternating current lighting system led Westinghouse to begin installing AC systems later that year.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1888 the first designs for an AC motor appeared.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These were induction motors running on polyphase current, independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Practical three-phase motors were designed by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Widespread use of such motors were delayed many years by development problems and the scarcity of polyphase power systems needed to power them.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the late 1880s and early 1890s smaller electric companies merged into larger corporations such as Ganz and AEG in Europe and General Electric and Westinghouse Electric in the US.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These companies developed AC systems, but the technical difference between direct and alternating current systems required a much longer technical merger.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Alternating current's economies of scale with large generating plants and long-distance transmission slowly added the ability to link all the loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These included single phase AC systems, poly-phase AC systems, low voltage incandescent lighting, high-voltage arc lighting, and existing DC motors in factories and street cars.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In what became a universal system, these technological differences were temporarily bridged via the rotary converters and motor-generators that allowed the legacy systems to connect to the AC grid.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These stopgaps were slowly replaced as older systems were retired or upgraded.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first transmission of single-phase alternating current using high voltage came in Oregon in 1890 when power was delivered from a hydroelectric plant at Willamette Falls to the city of Portland 14 miles (23 km) down river.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first three-phase alternating current using high voltage took place in 1891 during the international electricity exhibition in Frankfurt.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 15 kV transmission line, approximately 175 km long, connected Lauffen on the Neckar and Frankfurt.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission voltages increased throughout the 20th century.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] By 1914, fifty-five transmission systems operating at more than 70 kV were in service.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The highest voltage then used was 150 kV.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnecting multiple generating plants over a wide area reduced costs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The most efficient plants could be used to supply varying loads during the day.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reliability was improved and capital costs were reduced, because stand-by generating capacity could be shared over many more customers and a wider area.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Remote and low-cost sources of energy, such as hydroelectric power or mine-mouth coal, could be exploited to further lower costs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 20th century's rapid industrialization made electrical transmission lines and grids critical infrastructure.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnection of local generation plants and small distribution networks was spurred by World War I, when large electrical generating plants were built by governments to power munitions factories.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These networks use components such as power lines, cables, circuit breakers, switches and transformers.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission network is usually administered on a regional basis by an entity such as a regional transmission organization or transmission system operator.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission efficiency is improved at higher voltage and lower current.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The reduced current reduces heating losses.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Joule's first law states that energy losses are proportional to the square of the current.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, reducing the current by a factor of two lowers the energy lost to conductor resistance by a factor of four for any given size of conductor.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The optimum size of a conductor for a given voltage and current can be estimated by Kelvin's law for conductor size, which states that size is optimal when the annual cost of energy wasted in resistance is equal to the annual capital charges of providing the conductor.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] At times of lower interest rates and low commodity costs, Kelvin's law indicates that thicker wires are optimal.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Otherwise, thinner conductors are indicated.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since power lines are designed for long-term use, Kelvin's law is used in conjunction with long-term estimates of the price of copper and aluminum as well as interest rates.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher voltage is achieved in AC circuits by using a *step-up transformer*.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) systems require relatively costly conversion equipment that may be economically justified for particular projects such as submarine cables and longer distance high capacity point-to-point transmission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is necessary for sending energy between unsynchronized grids.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A transmission grid is a network of power stations, transmission lines, and substations.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Energy is usually transmitted within a grid with three-phase AC.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Single-phase AC is used only for distribution to end users since it is not usable for large polyphase induction motors.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the 19th century, two-phase transmission was used but required either four wires or three wires with unequal currents.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher order phase systems require more than three wires, but deliver little or no benefit.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] While the price of generating capacity is high, energy demand is variable, making it often cheaper to import needed power than to generate it locally.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because loads often rise and fall together across large areas, power often comes from distant sources.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of the economic benefits of load sharing, wide area transmission grids may span countries and even continents.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnections between producers and consumers enables power to flow even if some links are inoperative.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The slowly varying portion of demand is known as the *base load* and is generally served by large facilities with constant operating costs, termed firm power.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such facilities are nuclear, coal or hydroelectric, while other energy sources such as concentrated solar thermal and geothermal power have the potential to provide firm power.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Renewable energy sources, such as solar photovoltaics, wind, wave, and tidal, are, due to their intermittency, not considered to be firm.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The remaining or *peak* power demand, is supplied by peaking power plants, which are typically smaller, faster-responding, and higher cost sources, such as combined cycle or combustion turbine plants typically fueled by natural gas.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] New York often buys over 1000 MW of low-cost hydropower from Canada.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Local sources (even if more expensive and infrequently used) can protect the power supply from weather and other disasters that can disconnect distant suppliers.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Hydro and wind sources cannot be moved closer to big cities, and solar costs are lowest in remote areas where local power needs are nominal.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Connection costs can determine whether any particular renewable alternative is economically realistic.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Costs can be prohibitive for transmission lines, but high capacity, long distance super grid transmission network costs could be recovered with modest usage fees.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] At power stations, power is produced at a relatively low voltage between about 480 V and 22 kV, depending on the size of the unit.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage is then stepped up by the power station transformer to a higher voltage (100 kV to 1,000 kV AC) for transmission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, power transmission is, variously, 230 kV to 500 kV, with less than 230 kV or more than 500 kV as exceptions.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Western Interconnection has two primary interchange voltages: 500 kV AC at 60 Hz, and ±500 kV (1,000 kV net) DC from North to South (Columbia River to Southern California) and Northeast to Southwest (Utah to Southern California).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 287.5 kV (Hoover Dam to Los Angeles line, via Victorville) and 345 kV (Arizona Public Service (APS) line) are local standards, both of which were implemented before 500 kV became practical.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmitting electricity at high voltage reduces the fraction of energy lost to Joule heating, which varies by conductor type, the current, and the transmission distance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, a 100 miles (160 km) span at 765 kV carrying 1000 MW of power can have losses of 0.5% to 1.1%.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 345 kV line carrying the same load across the same distance has losses of 4.2%.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a given amount of power, a higher voltage reduces the current and thus the resistive losses.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, raising the voltage by a factor of 10 reduces the current by a corresponding factor of 10 and therefore the $I^{2}R$ losses by a factor of 100, provided the same sized conductors are used in both cases.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Even if the conductor size (cross-sectional area) is decreased ten-fold to match the lower current, the $I^{2}R$ losses are still reduced ten-fold using the higher voltage.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] While power loss can also be reduced by increasing the wire's conductance (by increasing its cross-sectional area), larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] And since conductance is proportional to cross-sectional area, resistive power loss is only reduced proportionally with increasing cross-sectional area, providing a much smaller benefit than the squared reduction provided by multiplying the voltage.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long-distance transmission is typically done with overhead lines at voltages of 115 to 1,200 kV.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] At higher voltages, where more than 2,000 kV exists between conductor and ground, corona discharge losses are so large that they can offset the lower resistive losses in the line conductors.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Measures to reduce corona losses include larger conductor diameter, hollow cores or conductor bundles.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Factors that affect resistance and thus loss include temperature, spiraling, and the skin effect.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spiraling, which refers to the way stranded conductors spiral about the center, also contributes to increases in conductor resistance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The skin effect causes the effective resistance to increase at higher AC frequencies.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Corona and resistive losses can be estimated using a mathematical model.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] US transmission and distribution losses were estimated at 6.6% in 1997, 6.5% in 2007 and 5% from 2013 to 2019.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In general, losses are estimated from the discrepancy between power produced (as reported by power plants) and power sold; the difference constitutes transmission and distribution losses, assuming no utility theft occurs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 1980, the longest cost-effective distance for DC transmission was 7,000 kilometres (4,300 miles).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For AC it was 4,000 kilometres (2,500 miles), though US transmission lines are substantially shorter.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In any AC line, conductor inductance and capacitance can be significant.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Currents that flow solely in reaction to these properties, (which together with the resistance define the impedance) constitute reactive power flow, which transmits no power to the load.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These reactive currents, however, cause extra heating losses.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The ratio of real power transmitted to the load to apparent power (the product of a circuit's voltage and current, without reference to phase angle) is the power factor.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As reactive current increases, reactive power increases and power factor decreases.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For transmission systems with low power factor, losses are higher than for systems with high power factor.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Utilities add capacitor banks, reactors and other components (such as phase-shifters; static VAR compensators; and flexible AC transmission systems, FACTS) throughout the system help to compensate for the reactive power flow, reduce the losses in power transmission and stabilize system voltages.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These measures are collectively called 'reactive support'.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Current flowing through transmission lines induces a magnetic field that surrounds the lines of each phase and affects the inductance of the surrounding conductors of other phases.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductors' mutual inductance is partially dependent on the physical orientation of the lines with respect to each other.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Three-phase lines are conventionally strung with phases separated vertically.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The mutual inductance seen by a conductor of the phase in the middle of the other two phases is different from the inductance seen on the top/bottom.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Unbalanced inductance among the three conductors is problematic because it may force the middle line to carry a disproportionate amount of the total power transmitted.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Similarly, an unbalanced load may occur if one line is consistently closest to the ground and operates at a lower impedance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of this phenomenon, conductors must be periodically transposed along the line so that each phase sees equal time in each relative position to balance out the mutual inductance seen by all three phases.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] To accomplish this, line position is swapped at specially designed transposition towers at regular intervals along the line using various transposition schemes.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission runs at relatively lower voltages.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is uneconomical to connect all distribution substations to the high main transmission voltage, because that equipment is larger and more expensive.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Typically, only larger substations connect with this high voltage.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage is stepped down before the current is sent to smaller substations.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission circuits are usually arranged in loops so that a single line failure does not stop service to many customers for more than a short time.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Loops can be *normally closed*, where loss of one circuit should result in no interruption, or *normally open* where substations can switch to a backup supply.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] While subtransmission circuits are usually carried on overhead lines, in urban areas buried cable may be used.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lower-voltage subtransmission lines use less right-of-way and simpler structures; undergrounding is less difficult.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] No fixed cutoff separates subtransmission and transmission, or subtransmission and distribution.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages of 69 kV, 115 kV, and 138 kV are often used for subtransmission in North America.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As power systems evolved, voltages formerly used for transmission were used for subtransmission, and subtransmission voltages became distribution voltages.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Like transmission, subtransmission moves relatively large amounts of power, and like distribution, subtransmission covers an area instead of just point-to-point.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Substation transformers reduce the voltage to a lower level for distribution to customers.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This distribution is accomplished with a combination of sub-transmission (33 to 138 kV) and distribution (3.3 to 25 kV).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Finally, at the point of use, the energy is transformed to end-user voltage (100 to 4160 volts).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage power transmission allows for lesser resistive losses over long distances.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This efficiency delivers a larger proportion of the generated power to the loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In a simplified model, the grid delivers electricity from an ideal voltage source with voltage V , delivering a power $P_{V}$ ) to a single point of consumption, modelled by a resistance R , when the wires are long enough to have a significant resistance $R_{C}$ .
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] If the resistances are in series with no intervening transformer, the circuit acts as a voltage divider, because the same current $I={\frac {V}{R+R_{C}}}$ runs through the wire resistance and the powered device.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For $a>1$ (i.e. conversion of high voltage to low voltage near the consumption point), a larger fraction of the generator's power is transmitted to the consumption point and a lesser fraction is lost to Joule heating.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The terminal characteristics of the transmission line are the voltage and current at the sending (S) and receiving (R) ends.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The line is assumed to be a reciprocal, symmetrical network, meaning that the receiving and sending labels can be switched with no consequence.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The parameters *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D* differ depending on how the desired model handles the line's resistance (*R*), inductance (*L*), capacitance (*C*), and shunt (parallel, leak) conductance *G*.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The four main models are the short line approximation, the medium line approximation, the long line approximation (with distributed parameters), and the lossless line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In such models, a capital letter such as *R* refers to the total quantity summed over the line and a lowercase letter such as *c* refers to the per-unit-length quantity.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lossless line approximation is the least accurate; it is typically used on short lines where the inductance is much greater than the resistance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For this approximation, the voltage and current are identical at the sending and receiving ends.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The characteristic impedance is pure real, which means resistive for that impedance, and it is often called surge impedance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] When a lossless line is terminated by surge impedance, the voltage does not drop.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Though the phase angles of voltage and current are rotated, the magnitudes of voltage and current remain constant along the line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load > SIL, the voltage drops from sending end and the line *consumes* VARs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load < SIL, the voltage increases from the sending end, and the line *generates* VARs.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The short line approximation is normally used for lines shorter than 80 km (50 mi).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] There, only a series impedance *Z* is considered, while *C* and *G* are ignored.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The final result is that A = D = 1 per unit, B = Z Ohms, and C = 0.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The medium line approximation is used for lines running between 80 and 250 km (50 and 155 mi).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The series impedance and the shunt (current leak) conductance are considered, placing half of the shunt conductance at each end of the line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This circuit is often referred to as a *nominal *π* (pi)* circuit because of the shape (*π*) that is taken on when leak conductance is placed on both sides of the circuit diagram.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The long line model is used when a higher degree of accuracy is needed or when the line under consideration is more than 250 km (160 mi) long.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series resistance and shunt conductance are considered to be distributed parameters, such that each differential length of the line has a corresponding differential series impedance and shunt admittance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The following result can be applied at any point along the transmission line, where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] To find the voltage and current at the end of the long line, x should be replaced with l (the line length) in all parameters of the transmission matrix.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This model applies the Telegrapher's equations.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) is used to transmit large amounts of power over long distances or for interconnections between asynchronous grids.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] When electrical energy is transmitted over very long distances, the power lost in AC transmission becomes appreciable and it is less expensive to use direct current instead.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a long transmission line, these lower losses (and reduced construction cost of a DC line) can offset the cost of the required converter stations at each end.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is used for long submarine cables where AC cannot be used because of cable capacitance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In these cases special high-voltage cables are used.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Submarine connections up to 600 kilometres (370 mi) in length have been deployed.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links can be used to control grid problems.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power transmitted by an AC line increases as the phase angle between source end voltage and destination ends increases, but too large a phase angle allows the systems at either end to fall out of step.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since the power flow in a DC link is controlled independently of the phases of the AC networks that it connects, this phase angle limit does not exist, and a DC link is always able to transfer its full rated power.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A DC link therefore stabilizes the AC grid at either end, since power flow and phase angle can then be controlled independently.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As an example, to adjust the flow of AC power on a hypothetical line between Seattle and Boston would require adjustment of the relative phase of the two regional electrical grids.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is an everyday occurrence in AC systems, but one that can become disrupted when AC system components fail and place unexpected loads on the grid.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] (and possibly in other cooperating cities along the transmission route).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such a system could be less prone to failure if parts of it were suddenly shut down.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] One example of a long DC transmission line is the Pacific DC Intertie located in the Western United States.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The amount of power that can be sent over a transmission line varies with the length of the line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The heating of short line conductors due to line losses sets a thermal limit.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] If too much current is drawn, conductors may sag too close to the ground, or conductors and equipment may overheat.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For intermediate-length lines on the order of 100 kilometres (62 miles), the limit is set by the voltage drop in the line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For longer AC lines, system stability becomes the limiting factor.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Approximately, the power flowing over an AC line is proportional to the cosine of the phase angle of the voltage and current at the ends.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This angle varies depending on system loading.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is undesirable for the angle to approach 90 degrees, as the power flowing decreases while resistive losses remain.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The product of line length and maximum load is approximately proportional to the square of the system voltage.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series capacitors or phase-shifting transformers are used on long lines to improve stability.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC lines are restricted only by thermal and voltage drop limits, since the phase angle is not material.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Understanding the temperature distribution along the cable route became possible with the introduction of distributed temperature sensing (DTS) systems that measure temperatures all along the cable.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Without them maximum current was typically set as a compromise between understanding of operation conditions and risk minimization.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This monitoring solution uses passive optical fibers as temperature sensors, either inside a high-voltage cable or externally mounted on the cable insulation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] For overhead cables the fiber is integrated into the core of a phase wire.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The integrated Dynamic Cable Rating (DCR)/Real Time Thermal Rating (RTTR) solution makes it possible to run the network to its maximum.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] It allows the operator to predict the behavior of the transmission system to reflect major changes to its initial operating conditions.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some utilities have embraced reconductoring to handle the increase in electricity production.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring is the replacement-in-place of existing transmission lines with higher-capacity lines.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adding transmission lines is difficult due to cost, permit intervals, and local opposition.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring has the potential to double the amount of electricity that can travel across a transmission line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 2024 report found the United States behind countries like Belgium and the Netherlands in adoption of this technique to accommodate electrification and renewable energy.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In April 2022, the Biden Administration streamlined environmental reviews for such projects, and in May 2022 announced competitive grants for them funded by the 2021 Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and 2022 Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The rate of transmission expansion needs to double to support ongoing electrification and reach emission reduction targets.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 2022, more than 10,000 power plant and energy storage projects were awaiting permission to connect to the US grid — 95% were zero-carbon resources.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] New power lines can take 10 years to plan, permit, and build.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Traditional power lines use a steel core surrounded by aluminum strands (Aluminium-conductor steel-reinforced cable).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Replacing the steel with a lighter, stronger composite material such as carbon fiber (ACCC conductor) allows lines to operate at higher temperatures, with less sag, and doubled transmission capacity.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lowering line sag at high temperatures can prevent wildfires from starting when power lines touch dry vegetation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Although advanced lines can cost 2-4x more than steel, total reconductoring costs are less than half of a new line, given savings in time, land acquisition, permitting, and construction.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A reconductoring project in southeastern Texas upgraded 240 miles of transmission lines at a cost of $900,000 per mile, versus a 3,600-mile greenfield project that averaged $1.9 million per mile.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] To ensure safe and predictable operation, system components are controlled with generators, switches, circuit breakers and loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage, power, frequency, load factor, and reliability capabilities of the transmission system are designed to provide cost effective performance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system provides for base load and peak load capability, with margins for safety and fault tolerance.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Peak load times vary by region largely due to the industry mix.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In hot and cold climates home air conditioning and heating loads affect the overall load.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] They are typically highest in the late afternoon in the hottest part of the year and in mid-mornings and mid-evenings in the coldest part of the year.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power requirements vary by season and time of day.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Distribution system designs always take the base load and the peak load into consideration.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system usually does not have a large buffering capability to match loads with generation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus generation has to be kept matched to the load, to prevent overloading generation equipment.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Multiple sources and loads can be connected to the transmission system and they must be controlled to provide orderly transfer of power.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In centralized power generation, only local control of generation is necessary.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This involves synchronization of the generation units.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In distributed power generation the generators are geographically distributed and the process to bring them online and offline must be carefully controlled.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The load control signals can either be sent on separate lines or on the power lines themselves.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage and frequency can be used as signaling mechanisms to balance the loads.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In voltage signaling, voltage is varied to increase generation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power added by any system increases as the line voltage decreases.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This arrangement is stable in principle.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage-based regulation is complex to use in mesh networks, since the individual components and setpoints would need to be reconfigured every time a new generator is added to the mesh.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In frequency signaling, the generating units match the frequency of the power transmission system.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In droop speed control, if the frequency decreases, the power is increased.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind turbines, vehicle-to-grid, virtual power plants, and other locally distributed storage and generation systems can interact with the grid to improve system operation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Internationally, a slow move from a centralized to decentralized power systems have taken place.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The main draw of locally distributed generation systems is that they reduce transmission losses by leading to consumption of electricity closer to where it was produced.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Under excess load conditions, the system can be designed to fail incrementally rather than all at once.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Brownouts occur when power supplied drops below the demand.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Blackouts occur when the grid fails completely.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rolling blackouts (also called load shedding) are intentionally engineered electrical power outages, used to distribute insufficient power to various loads in turn.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Grid operators require reliable communications to manage the grid and associated generation and distribution facilities.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Fault-sensing protective relays at each end of the line must communicate to monitor the flow of power so that faulted conductors or equipment can be quickly de-energized and the balance of the system restored.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Protection of the transmission line from short circuits and other faults is usually so critical that common carrier telecommunications are insufficiently reliable, while in some remote areas no common carrier is available.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rarely, and for short distances, pilot-wires are strung along the transmission line path.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Leased circuits from common carriers are not preferred since availability is not under control of the operator.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines can be used to carry data: this is called power-line carrier, or power-line communication (PLC).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] PLC signals can be easily received with a radio in the long wave range.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Optical fibers can be included in the stranded conductors of a transmission line, in the overhead shield wires.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These cables are known as optical ground wire (*OPGW*).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Sometimes a standalone cable is used, all-dielectric self-supporting (*ADSS*) cable, attached to the transmission line cross arms.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some jurisdictions, such as Minnesota, prohibit energy transmission companies from selling surplus communication bandwidth or acting as a telecommunications common carrier.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Where the regulatory structure permits, the utility can sell capacity in extra dark fibers to a common carrier.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity transmission is generally considered to be a natural monopoly, but one that is not inherently linked to generation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Many countries regulate transmission separately from generation.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain was the first country to establish a regional transmission organization.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In that country, transmission operations and electricity markets are separate.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system operator is Red Eléctrica de España (REE) and the wholesale electricity market operator is Operador del Mercado Ibérico de Energía – Polo Español, S.A.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain's transmission system is interconnected with those of France, Portugal, and Morocco.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The establishment of RTOs in the United States was spurred by the FERC's Order 888, *Promoting Wholesale Competition Through Open Access Non-discriminatory Transmission Services by Public Utilities; Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and Transmitting Utilities*, issued in 1996.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States and parts of Canada, electric transmission companies operate independently of generation companies, but in the Southern United States vertical integration is intact.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In regions of separation, transmission owners and generation owners continue to interact with each other as market participants with voting rights within their RTO.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] RTOs in the United States are regulated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Merchant transmission projects in the United States include the Cross Sound Cable from Shoreham, New York to New Haven, Connecticut, Neptune RTS Transmission Line from Sayreville, New Jersey, to New Bridge, New York, and Path 15 in California.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Additional projects are in development or have been proposed throughout the United States, including the Lake Erie Connector, an underwater transmission line proposed by ITC Holdings Corp., connecting Ontario to load serving entities in the PJM Interconnection region.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Australia has one unregulated or market interconnector – Basslink – between Tasmania and Victoria.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Two DC links originally implemented as market interconnectors, Directlink and Murraylink, were converted to regulated interconnectors.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A major barrier to wider adoption of merchant transmission is the difficulty in identifying who benefits from the facility so that the beneficiaries pay the toll.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Also, it is difficult for a merchant transmission line to compete when the alternative transmission lines are subsidized by utilities with a monopolized and regulated rate base.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, the FERC's Order 1000, issued in 2010, attempted to reduce barriers to third party investment and creation of merchant transmission lines where a public policy need is found.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The cost of high voltage transmission is comparatively low, compared to all other costs constituting consumer electricity bills.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the UK, transmission costs are about 0.2 p per kWh compared to a delivered domestic price of around 10 p per kWh.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The level of capital expenditure in the electric power T&D equipment market was estimated to be $128.9 bn in 2011.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Mainstream scientific evidence suggests that low-power, low-frequency, electromagnetic radiation associated with household currents and high transmission power lines does not constitute a short- or long-term health hazard.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some studies failed to find any link between living near power lines and developing any sickness or diseases, such as cancer.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 1997 study reported no increased risk of cancer or illness from living near a transmission line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Other studies, however, reported statistical correlations between various diseases and living or working near power lines.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] No adverse health effects have been substantiated for people not living close to power lines.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The New York State Public Service Commission conducted a study to evaluate potential health effects of electric fields.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The study measured the electric field strength at the edge of an existing right-of-way on a 765 kV transmission line.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The field strength was 1.6 kV/m, and became the interim maximum strength standard for new transmission lines in New York State.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The opinion also limited the voltage of new transmission lines built in New York to 345 kV.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] On September 11, 1990, after a similar study of magnetic field strengths, the NYSPSC issued their *Interim Policy Statement on Magnetic Fields*.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] This policy established a magnetic field standard of 200 mG at the edge of the right-of-way using the winter-normal conductor rating.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] As a comparison with everyday items, a hair dryer or electric blanket produces a 100 mG – 500 mG magnetic field.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Applications for a new transmission line typically include an analysis of electric and magnetic field levels at the edge of rights-of-way.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Public utility commissions typically do not comment on health impacts.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Biological effects have been established for acute high level exposure to magnetic fields above 100 μT (1 G) (1,000 mG).
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] These levels exceed average residential power-frequency magnetic fields in homes, which are about 0.07 μT (0.7 mG) in Europe and 0.11 μT (1.1 mG) in North America.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Earth's natural geomagnetic field strength varies over the surface of the planet between 0.035 mT and 0.07 mT (35 μT – 70 μT or 350 mG – 700 mG) while the international standard for continuous exposure is set at 40 mT (400,000 mG or 400 G) for the general public.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p01] Tree growth regulators and herbicides may be used in transmission line right of ways, which may have health effects.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] In some countries where electric locomotives or electric multiple units run on low frequency AC power, separate single phase traction power networks are operated by the railways.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Prime examples are countries such as Austria, Germany and Switzerland that utilize AC technology based on 16 2*/*3 Hz.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Norway and Sweden also use this frequency but use conversion from the 50 Hz public supply; Sweden has a 16 2*/*3 Hz traction grid but only for part of the system.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] High-temperature superconductors (HTS) promise to revolutionize power distribution by providing lossless transmission.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] The development of superconductors with transition temperatures higher than the boiling point of liquid nitrogen has made the concept of superconducting power lines commercially feasible, at least for high-load applications.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] It has been estimated that waste would be halved using this method, since the necessary refrigeration equipment would consume about half the power saved by the elimination of resistive losses.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Companies such as Consolidated Edison and American Superconductor began commercial production of such systems in 2007.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Superconducting cables are particularly suited to high load density areas such as the business district of large cities, where purchase of an easement for cables is costly.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return (SWER) or single-wire ground return is a single-wire transmission line for supplying single-phase electrical power to remote areas at low cost.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] It is principally used for rural electrification, but also finds use for larger isolated loads such as water pumps.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return is also used for HVDC over submarine power cables.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Both Nikola Tesla and Hidetsugu Yagi attempted to devise systems for large scale wireless power transmission in the late 1800s and early 1900s, without commercial success.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] In November 2009, LaserMotive won the NASA 2009 Power Beaming Challenge by powering a cable climber 1 km vertically using a ground-based laser transmitter.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] The system produced up to 1 kW of power at the receiver end.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] In August 2010, NASA contracted with private companies to pursue the design of laser power beaming systems to power low earth orbit satellites and to launch rockets using laser power beams.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Wireless power transmission has been studied for transmission of power from solar power satellites to the earth.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] A high power array of microwave or laser transmitters would beam power to a rectenna.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] Major engineering and economic challenges face any solar power satellite project.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] The federal government of the United States stated that the American power grid was susceptible to cyber-warfare.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] The United States Department of Homeland Security works with industry to identify vulnerabilities and to help industry enhance the security of control system networks.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] In June 2019, Russia conceded that it was "possible" its electrical grid is under cyber-attack by the United States.
[src:iec-60870/electric-power-transmission-p02] *The New York Times* reported that American hackers from the United States Cyber Command planted malware potentially capable of disrupting the Russian electrical grid.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] IEC 60870-5-101/102/103/104 are companion standards generated for basic telecontrol tasks, transmission of integrated totals, data exchange from protection equipment and network access of IEC101 respectively.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] IEC 60870-5-101 [IEC101] is a standard for power system monitoring, control & associated communications for telecontrol, teleprotection, and associated telecommunications for electric power systems.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] This is completely compatible with IEC 60870-5-1 to IEC 60870-5-5 standards and uses standard asynchronous serial tele-control channel interface between DTE and DCE.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The standard is suitable for multiple configurations like point-to-point, star, multidrop etc.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The character format of IEC 101 uses 1 bit each for start, stop and parity, as well as 8 data bits.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] FT1.2 (defined in IEC 60870-5-1) is used for frame format of IEC 101 which is suitable for asynchronous serial communication with Hamming distance of 4.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] This uses 3 types of frame formats - *Frame with variable length ASDU*, *Frame with fixed length* & *single character*.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Single character is used for acknowledgments, fixed length frames are used for commands & variable lengths are used for sending data.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] IEC 60870-5-103 [IEC103] is a standard for power system control and associated communications.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] It defines a companion standard that enables interoperability between protection equipment and devices of a control system in a substation.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The device complying with this standard can send the information using two methods for data transfer - either using the explicitly specified application service data units (ASDU) or using generic services for transmission of all the possible information.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The standard supports some specific protection functions and provides the vendor a facility to incorporate its own protective functions on private data ranges.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] IEC 103 uses FT1.2 (defined in IEC 60870-5-1) for frame format having options of *Frame with variable length*, *Frame with fixed length* & *single character* similar to IEC 101.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] However the frame format of IEC 103 differs from IEC 101 in information object address which is split into function type (ftype) and information number (inumber) in IEC 103.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Also IEC 103 can have only single information object in a frame whereas IEC 101 can have multiple information objects.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Many of the field sizes are also restricted in IEC 103.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] IEC 60870-5-104 (IEC 104) protocol is an extension of IEC 101 protocol with the changes in transport, network, link, and physical layer services to suit the complete network access.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The standard uses an open TCP/IP interface to network to have connectivity to the LAN (local area network) and routers with different facility (ISDN, X.25, Frame Relay etc.) can be used to connect to the wide area network (WAN).
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Application layer of IEC 104 is preserved same as that of IEC 101 with some of the data types and facilities not used.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] There are two separate link layers defined in the standard, which is suitable for data transfer over Ethernet & serial line (PPP - Point-to-Point Protocol).
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The control field data of IEC104 contains various types of mechanisms for effective handling of network data synchronization.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] The security of IEC 104, by design has been proven to be problematic, as many of the other SCADA protocols developed around the same time.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Though the IEC technical committee (TC) 57 have published a security standard IEC 62351, which implements encryption tunneling and network monitoring in an effort to address attacks such as packet replay and man-in-the-middle.
[src:iec-60870/iec-60870-5] Due to the increase in complexity and cost, system owners are reluctant to roll this out on their networks.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Other terms that may be used for RTU are **remote telemetry unit** and **remote telecontrol unit**.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU monitors the field digital and analog parameters and transmits data to a SCADA Master Station.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] It runs setup software to connect data input streams to data output streams, define communication protocols, and troubleshoot installation problems in the field.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU might even be a small process control unit with a small database for PID, Alarming, Filtering, Trending and other functions complemented with some BASIC (programming language) tasks.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs typically support the IEC 61131-3 programming standard for programmable logic controllers.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] For example, it communicates via RS485 or wireless communication links in a multi-drop configuration.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] In this type of configuration it is a remote unit that collects data and performs simple control tasks.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] It does not have moving parts and uses extremely low power and is often solar powered.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] A form of power supply will be included for operation from the AC mains for various CPU, status wetting voltages and other interface cards.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] This may consist of AC to DC converters where operated from a station battery system.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may include a battery and charger circuitry to continue operation in event of AC power failure for critical applications where a station battery is not available.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Most RTUs have a section called *input status cards* to read ON/OFF information from the field.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] They do this by checking if a contact (like a switch) is open or closed at the RTU location.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Some RTUs can also count events (like how many times a contact opens/closes), but this is optional.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can monitor analog inputs of different types including 0-1 mA, 4–20 mA current loop, 0–10 V., ±2.5 V, ±5.0 V etc.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Many RTU inputs buffer larger quantities via transducers to convert and isolate real-world quantities from sensitive RTU input levels.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can also receive analog data via a communication system from a master or intelligent electronic device (IED) sending data values to it.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] The RTU or host system translates and scales this raw data into the appropriate units such as the quantity of water left, temperature degrees, or Megawatts, before presenting the data to the user via the human–machine interface.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may drive high current capacity relays to a digital output (or "DO") board to switch power on and off to devices in the field.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] The DO board switches voltage to the coil in the relay, which closes the high current contacts, which completes the power circuit to the device.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] RTU outputs may also consist of driving a sensitive logic input on an electronic PLC, or other electronic device using a sensitive 5 V input.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] While not as commonly used, analog outputs may be included to control devices that require varying quantities, such as graphic recording instruments (strip charts).
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Summed or processed data quantities may be generated in a master SCADA system and output for display locally or remotely, wherever needed.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs are usually capable of executing simple programs autonomously without involving the host computers of the DCS or SCADA system to simplify deployment and to provide redundancy for safety reasons.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU in a modern water management system will typically have code to modify its behavior when physical override switches on the RTU are toggled during maintenance-by-maintenance personnel.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] This is done for safety reasons; a miscommunication between the system operators and the maintenance personnel could cause system operators to mistakenly enable power to a water pump when it is being replaced, for example.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Maintenance personnel should have any equipment they are working on disconnected from power and locked to prevent damage and/or injury.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may be interfaced to multiple master stations and IEDs with different communication protocols (usually serial (RS-232, RS-485, RS-422) or Ethernet).
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may support standard protocols (Modbus, IEC 60870-5-101/103/104, DNP3, IEC 60870-6-ICCP, IEC 61850 etc.) to interface any third-party software.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Data transfer may be initiated from either end using various techniques to ensure synchronization with minimal data traffic.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] The master may poll its subordinate unit (Master to RTU or RTU to IED) for changes of data on a periodic basis.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Analog value changes will usually be reported only on changes outside a set limit from the last transmitted value.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Digital (status) values observe a similar technique and only transmit groups (bytes) when one included point (bit) changes.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Another method used is where a subordinate unit initiates an update of data upon a predetermined change in analog or digital data.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Complete data transmission must be performed periodically, with either method, to ensure full synchronization and eliminate stale data.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Most communication protocols support both methods, programmable by the installer.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Multiple RTUs or IEDs may share a communications line, in a multi-drop scheme, as units are addressed uniquely and only respond to their own polls and commands.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] IED communications transfer data between the RTU and an IED.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] This can eliminate the need for many hardware status inputs, analog inputs, and relay outputs in the RTU.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Communications are accomplished by copper or fibre optics lines.
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Master communications usually occur between an RTU and a larger control system or a data collection system (incorporated into a larger system).
[src:iec-60870/remote-terminal-unit] Data may be moved using a copper, fibre optic or radio frequency communication system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:iec-60870/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:iec-60870/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:iec-60870/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:iec-60870/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:iec-60870/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:iec-60870/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:iec-60870/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:iec-60870/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:iec-60870/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:iec-60870/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:iec-60870/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:iec-60870/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:iec-60870/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:iec-60870/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:iec-60870/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:iec-60870/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:iec-60870/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:iec-60870/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:iec-60870/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:iec-60870/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:iec-60870/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:iec-60870/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:iec-60870/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:iec-60870/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:iec-60870/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:iec-60870/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:iec-60870/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:iec-60870/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:iec-60870/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:iec-60870/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:iec-60870/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:iec-60870/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:iec-60870/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:iec-60870/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:iec-60870/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:iec-60870/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:iec-60870/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:iec-60870/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] A **telecommand** or **telecontrol** is a command sent to control a remote system or systems not directly connected (e.g. via wires) to the place from which the telecommand is sent.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] The word is derived from *tele* = remote (Greek), and *command* = to entrust/order (Latin).
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Systems that need remote measurement and reporting of information of interest to the system designer or operator require the counterpart of telecommand, telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] The *telecommand* can be done in real time or not depending on the circumstances (in space, delay may be of days), as was the case of Marsokhod.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Examples include a television remote control, remote guidance of weapons or missiles, control of a satellite from a ground station, and flying a radio-controlled airplane.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] For a Telecommand (TC) to be effective, it must be compiled into a pre-arranged format (which may follow a standard structure), modulated onto a carrier wave which is then transmitted with adequate power to the remote system.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] The remote system will then demodulate the digital signal from the carrier, decode the TC, and execute it.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Transmission of the carrier wave can be by ultrasound, infra-red or other electromagnetic means.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Infrared light makes up the invisible section of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] This light, also classified as heat, transmits signals between the transmitter and receiver of the remote system.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Telecommand systems usually include a physical remote, which contains four key parts: buttons, integrated circuit, button contacts, and a light-emitting diode.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] When the buttons on a remote are pressed they touch and close their corresponding contacts below them within the remote.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] This completes the necessary circuit on the circuit board along with a change in electrical resistance, which is detected by the integrated circuit.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Based on the change in electrical resistance, the integrated circuit distinguishes which button was pushed and sends a corresponding binary code to the light-emitting diode (LED) usually located at the front of the remote.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] To transfer the information from the remote to the receiver, the LED turns the electrical signals into an invisible beam of infrared light that corresponds with the binary code and sends this light to the receiver.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] The receiver then detects the light signal via a photodiode and it is transformed into an electrical signal for the command and is sent to the receiver’s integrated circuit/microprocessor to process and complete the command.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] The strength of the transmitting LED can vary and determines the required positioning accuracy of the remote in relevance to the receiver.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Infrared remotes have a maximum range of approximately 30 feet and require the remote control or transmitter and receiver to be within a line of sight.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Ultrasonic is a technology used more frequently in the past for telecommand.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Inventor Robert Adler is known for inventing the remote control which did not require batteries and used ultrasonic technology.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] There are four aluminum rods inside the transmitter that produce high frequency sounds when they are hit at one end.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Each rod is a different length, which enables them to produce varying sound pitches, which control the receiving unit.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] This technology was widely used but had certain issues such as dogs being bothered by the high frequency sounds.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Often the smaller new remote controlled airplanes and helicopters are incorrectly advertised as radio controlled devices (see Radio control) but they are either controlled via infra-red transmission or electromagnetically guided.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] Both of these systems are part of the telecommand area.
[src:iec-60870/telecontrol] To prevent unauthorised access to the remote system, TC encryption may be employed.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:iec-60870/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
